In modern computers, a specialized register called a Floating-Point Register (FPR) is used to hold floating-point values.
Unlike general-purpose registers that typically handle integers, these registers are part of the Floating-Point Unit (FPU), which is designed specifically for decimal and scientific math.

Common Register Types:

x86/x64 Architecture: Modern Intel and AMD processors use XMM, YMM, or ZMM registers. 
These are large registers (128-bit to 512-bit) that can hold multiple floating-point values at once for faster processing.
Which in starndard windows and amd64 linux architecture

ARM: Uses specialized registers that can hold single (32-bit), double (64-bit), or extended precision values. Which in arm64 system (phone, ipad,...)


both use IEEE 754

Every IEEE 754 number is composed of three distinct fields: 

Sign Bit: A single bit where 0 represents a positive number and 1 represents a negative number.
Biased Exponent: Represents the power of 2 that the number is multiplied by. A "bias" is added to the actual exponent to avoid using a separate sign bit for negative powers.
Mantissa (Significand): Represents the significant digits of the number. In "normalized" form, an implicit leading 1 is assumed and not stored, providing an extra bit of precision for free. 

